---
import ResourceLayout from '../../components/ResourceLayout.astro';
---

<ResourceLayout
  icon="💊"
  eyebrow="Medicines and pharmacies"
  title="Medications"
  introduction="Learn how prescriptions work, what pharmacies do, and how to take medications safely in Canada."
>
  <section>
    <h2>What is a prescription?</h2>
    <p>
      A prescription is a medication that must be authorized by a licensed
      healthcare provider such as a physician or nurse practitioner. Take the
      prescription to a pharmacy, where a pharmacist will prepare and dispense
      the medication.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The role of a pharmacist</h2>
    <p>
      Pharmacists are healthcare professionals who explain how to take your
      medication, answer questions about side effects, check for drug
      interactions, and help ensure medicines are used safely.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Prescription vs. over-the-counter medicines</h2>
    <p>
      Some medicines require a prescription, while others can be purchased
      directly from a pharmacy or grocery store. Even over-the-counter
      medications can have side effects or interact with other medicines.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Refills</h2>
    <p>
      Some prescriptions include refills, allowing you to obtain more medication
      without seeing your healthcare provider again. If no refills remain, you
      may need a new prescription before the pharmacy can dispense additional
      medication.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Medication safety</h2>
    <p>
      Always take medications exactly as directed. Do not share prescription
      medicines with others, and tell your healthcare provider and pharmacist
      about all medications, vitamins, and herbal supplements you are taking.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Generic and brand-name medications</h2>
    <p>
      Generic medications contain the same active ingredient as the brand-name
      version and are carefully regulated for quality and effectiveness. They
      are often a more affordable option.
    </p>
  </section>

  <aside class="notice">
    <strong>Questions about your medicine?</strong>
    <p>
      If you are unsure how to take a medication, experience unexpected side
      effects, or think you may have taken the wrong dose, contact your
      pharmacist or healthcare provider before making changes whenever possible.
      If someone has severe difficulty breathing, collapses, or has a suspected
      overdose, call 911 immediately.
    </p>
  </aside>
</ResourceLayout>